263
00:13:09,540 --> 00:13:14,340
 So what happened next?

264
00:13:14,340 --> 00:13:16,460
 I mean, was Paul released?

265
00:13:16,460 --> 00:13:19,780
 Was he brought to trial before the emperor?

266
00:13:19,780 --> 00:13:22,340
 Was he convicted and martyred?

267
00:13:22,340 --> 00:13:24,180
 We are not told.

268
00:13:24,180 --> 00:13:30,300
 I thought, what a strange way to end.

269
00:13:30,300 --> 00:13:35,140
 Why on earth does Luke end this way?

270
00:13:35,140 --> 00:13:41,260
 Perhaps, perhaps he finished writing Acts

271
00:13:41,260 --> 00:13:43,620
 while Paul was still in prison.

272
00:13:43,620 --> 00:13:46,640
 That would be about 62 AD.

273
00:13:46,640 --> 00:13:50,220
 And that this was as far as the story had got.

274
00:13:50,220 --> 00:13:53,140
 But this is very unlikely,

275
00:13:53,140 --> 00:13:57,180
 since Luke almost certainly wrote it after 70

276
00:13:57,180 --> 00:14:00,300
 because he used Mark's gospel as a source.

277
00:14:00,300 --> 00:14:02,600
 And Mark was written about 70.

278
00:14:02,600 --> 00:14:07,620
 So Luke probably writing in AD 80s,

279
00:14:07,620 --> 00:14:10,900
 intended to end it here.

280
00:14:10,900 --> 00:14:15,060
 Why?

281
00:14:15,060 --> 00:14:22,420
 Well, what is the book of Acts all about?

282
00:14:22,420 --> 00:14:25,460
 Is it about the life of Paul?

283
00:14:25,460 --> 00:14:27,220
 No.

284
00:14:27,220 --> 00:14:30,620
 What is it about?

285
00:14:30,620 --> 00:14:36,540
 And most scholars agree that Acts 1:8 is the theme.

286
00:14:36,540 --> 00:14:40,740
 It's a methodical statement.

287
00:14:40,740 --> 00:14:45,180
 It's a critical verse, the words of the risen Jesus.

288
00:14:45,180 --> 00:14:46,780
 And he said this,

289
00:14:46,780 --> 00:14:52,020
 "But you will receive power

290
00:14:52,020 --> 00:14:56,500
 "when the Holy Spirit has come upon you.

291
00:14:56,500 --> 00:15:03,760
 "And you will be my witnesses in Jerusalem,

292
00:15:03,760 --> 00:15:06,420
 "in all Judea and Samaria,

293
00:15:06,420 --> 00:15:09,580
 "and to the ends of the earth."

294
00:15:10,140 --> 00:15:15,140
 Acts is not a general history of the early church.

295
00:15:15,140 --> 00:15:20,100
 It is not everything that Luke knows

296
00:15:20,100 --> 00:15:22,420
 about the history of the early Christianity.

297
00:15:22,420 --> 00:15:24,180
 It is too limited for that.

298
00:15:24,180 --> 00:15:27,400
 There's too much that he's left out.

299
00:15:27,400 --> 00:15:33,100
 Rather, I believe that the book of Acts

300
00:15:33,100 --> 00:15:38,100
 is the development, the working out of Acts 1:8.

301
00:15:39,100 --> 00:15:44,100
 So it's about the Holy Spirit coming upon them.

302
00:15:44,100 --> 00:15:49,020
 The book of Acts is sometimes called

303
00:15:49,020 --> 00:15:51,500
 the book of the Holy Spirit,

304
00:15:51,500 --> 00:15:53,580
 the Acts of the Holy Spirit.

305
00:15:53,580 --> 00:15:56,280
 We have Pentecost,

306
00:15:56,280 --> 00:16:00,140
 then Peter, full of the Holy Spirit,

307
00:16:00,140 --> 00:16:03,900
 addressing the Sanhedrin in Acts 4.

308
00:16:03,900 --> 00:16:07,900
 Then the Spirit falling on the new believers in Samaria.

309
00:16:08,900 --> 00:16:13,420
 The Spirit forbidding Paul to go to certain places

310
00:16:13,420 --> 00:16:15,580
 and then guiding him to others.

311
00:16:15,580 --> 00:16:20,580
 The Holy Spirit is mentioned 59 times in the book of Acts.

312
00:16:20,580 --> 00:16:29,620
 And the book of Acts is about being witnesses.

313
00:16:29,620 --> 00:16:36,040
 Witnesses to Jesus.

314
00:16:36,040 --> 00:16:36,940
 He said, didn't he?

315
00:16:36,940 --> 00:16:40,060
 "You will be my witnesses."

316
00:16:40,060 --> 00:16:43,060
 I mean, think of Stephen.

317
00:16:43,060 --> 00:16:45,500
 Think of Paul, Peter, Philip.

318
00:16:45,500 --> 00:16:48,320
 We examine them all.

319
00:16:48,320 --> 00:16:56,520
 But witnessing is a rather foreboding word, isn't it?

320
00:16:56,520 --> 00:17:03,300
 I have to say it's somewhat of a dirty word

321
00:17:03,300 --> 00:17:06,580
 in some church circles.

322
00:17:06,580 --> 00:17:11,200
 Everyone says, "Oh, my faith, it's personal."

323
00:17:11,200 --> 00:17:17,080
 But in Acts, it's simply telling a story.

324
00:17:17,080 --> 00:17:19,660
 The story of Jesus,

325
00:17:19,660 --> 00:17:23,660
 the story of how Jesus changed someone's life.

326
00:17:23,660 --> 00:17:27,000
 The story of how Jesus changed the whole community.

327
00:17:27,000 --> 00:17:32,900
 And it is about being witnesses in Jerusalem, Judea, Samaria

328
00:17:35,100 --> 00:17:36,700
 to the ends of the earth.

329
00:17:36,700 --> 00:17:42,620
 So Luke tells this story.

330
00:17:42,620 --> 00:17:48,780
 Jerusalem first, then they go to Samaria

331
00:17:48,780 --> 00:17:52,580
 and then the gospel expands.

332
00:17:52,580 --> 00:17:56,380
 Does it reach the ends of the earth?

333
00:17:56,380 --> 00:18:00,820
 Actually, where are the ends of the earth anyway?

334
00:18:01,980 --> 00:18:02,940
 Rome?

335
00:18:02,940 --> 00:18:03,980
 Heck no.

336
00:18:03,980 --> 00:18:06,400
 From a Greco-Roman perspective,

337
00:18:06,400 --> 00:18:09,940
 Rome was the center of the earth.

338
00:18:09,940 --> 00:18:12,020
 If you go back to Luke chapter one,

339
00:18:12,020 --> 00:18:15,820
 or Luke chapter two, sorry, our Christmas narrative,

340
00:18:15,820 --> 00:18:18,660
 we read of a decree going out

341
00:18:18,660 --> 00:18:21,300
 from the Emperor Augustus in Rome

342
00:18:21,300 --> 00:18:24,540
 to the whole inhabited world.

343
00:18:24,540 --> 00:18:27,060
 Rome was the center.

344
00:18:28,660 --> 00:18:32,820
 But for either Greeks or Jews or Romans,

345
00:18:32,820 --> 00:18:36,380
 the world extends far beyond Rome

346
00:18:36,380 --> 00:18:40,340
 to the rest of Europe, to Spain,

347
00:18:40,340 --> 00:18:45,340
 and onwards to America, Africa, Asia, Hong Kong.

348
00:18:45,340 --> 00:18:56,620
 The ends of the earth is the ends of the earth.

349
00:18:57,620 --> 00:19:00,500
 So why does Acts end in Rome?

350
00:19:00,500 --> 00:19:03,700
 Endings matter.

351
00:19:03,700 --> 00:19:07,540
 Why end in Rome?

352
00:19:07,540 --> 00:19:09,420
 I'll tell you why.

353
00:19:09,420 --> 00:19:16,820
 The story is not complete.

354
00:19:16,820 --> 00:19:23,140
 The story is not complete.

355
00:19:25,140 --> 00:19:27,300
 The story is not complete.

356
00:19:27,300 --> 00:19:32,300
 Acts 1, 8 is not fulfilled with Paul's arrival in Rome.

357
00:19:32,300 --> 00:19:35,180
 Witnesses to be to the ends of the earth.

358
00:19:35,180 --> 00:19:40,900
 That is a target beyond Rome, which is not reached in Acts.

359
00:19:40,900 --> 00:19:47,060
 But the crucial point is that the ending of Acts

360
00:19:47,060 --> 00:19:48,780
 is a non-ending.

361
00:19:48,780 --> 00:19:53,020
 It is not an ending at all.

362
00:19:54,580 --> 00:19:55,420
 Why not?

363
00:19:55,420 --> 00:20:01,540
 Because Luke intended a volume three.

364
00:20:01,540 --> 00:20:05,500
 He intended an Acts 29.

365
00:20:05,500 --> 00:20:09,260
 Not one that he would write,

366
00:20:09,260 --> 00:20:13,420
 but one that the Holy Spirit would write

367
00:20:13,420 --> 00:20:15,580
 in the life of the church.

368
00:20:15,580 --> 00:20:20,060
 Like a movie where the movie writer

369
00:20:20,060 --> 00:20:22,940
 ends with a sequel in mind.

370
00:20:22,940 --> 00:20:25,060
 Like "The Lord of the Rings"

371
00:20:25,060 --> 00:20:26,980
 or "The Pirates of the Caribbean."

372
00:20:26,980 --> 00:20:33,780
 But in this case, Luke is not gonna write volume three.

373
00:20:33,780 --> 00:20:39,580
 Rather, the Holy Spirit will.

374
00:20:39,580 --> 00:20:45,260
 With future Christians as actors.

375
00:20:45,260 --> 00:20:49,540
 That's us.

376
00:20:49,540 --> 00:20:54,540
 We are part of the cast of Acts.

377
00:20:54,540 --> 00:21:02,220
 But as a sort of prelude to volume three and Acts 29,

378
00:21:02,220 --> 00:21:05,820
 I wanna look at how Luke ends volume two

379
00:21:05,820 --> 00:21:09,020
 in Acts chapter 27 and 28.

380
00:21:09,020 --> 00:21:14,020
 And to do that, I want to tell you a story.

381
00:21:14,020 --> 00:21:17,140
 It's the story of a journey

382
00:21:18,460 --> 00:21:21,580
 and a very eventful journey.

383
00:21:21,580 --> 00:21:25,300
 A trip across the Mediterranean Sea

384
00:21:25,300 --> 00:21:29,260
 that certainly was not a pleasure cruise.

385
00:21:29,260 --> 00:21:34,940
 To help us navigate, I put a map on the screen.

386
00:21:34,940 --> 00:21:39,060
 We're gonna start with our first scene,

387
00:21:39,060 --> 00:21:43,260
 which is starting out by sailing to Rome.

388
00:21:43,260 --> 00:21:47,860
 As we open the story in Acts 27, we are at Caesarea.

389
00:21:48,860 --> 00:21:52,020
 And we are confronted with the statement,

390
00:21:52,020 --> 00:21:57,020
 when it was decided that we would sail for Italy.

391
00:21:57,020 --> 00:22:02,380
 That suggests that Paul did not travel alone to Rome,

392
00:22:02,380 --> 00:22:05,740
 but that Luke and perhaps other disciples

393
00:22:05,740 --> 00:22:08,320
 accompanied Paul on his journey.

394
00:22:08,320 --> 00:22:12,660
 We certainly know of at least one more disciple

395
00:22:12,660 --> 00:22:14,300
 that traveled with Paul.

396
00:22:14,300 --> 00:22:16,740
 His name was Aristarchus.

397
00:22:16,740 --> 00:22:19,800
 Because he was mentioned by Paul in Colossians

398
00:22:19,800 --> 00:22:21,800
 as a fellow prisoner.

399
00:22:21,800 --> 00:22:27,860
 From the record, it seems that the Roman governor Festus

400
00:22:27,860 --> 00:22:31,060
 placed Paul and the Roman escorts

401
00:22:31,060 --> 00:22:33,820
 on what we would call a freighter ship

402
00:22:33,820 --> 00:22:38,220
 that would make many steps on the way to Italy,

403
00:22:38,220 --> 00:22:39,980
 dropping off and picking off points.

404
00:22:39,980 --> 00:22:42,780
 I suppose an old-fashioned deliveroo probably.

405
00:22:44,260 --> 00:22:48,460
 Whilst unloading cargo at Sidon,

406
00:22:48,460 --> 00:22:53,140
 Paul was allowed to go and see his friends in that city.

407
00:22:53,140 --> 00:23:00,360
 Now the story continues as Luke recounts for us

408
00:23:00,360 --> 00:23:03,460
 the difficulty of their travel.

409
00:23:03,460 --> 00:23:08,460
 It was the time of year that the winds had shifted

410
00:23:09,580 --> 00:23:14,580
 and made sailing a long and dangerous task.

411
00:23:14,580 --> 00:23:18,980
 Verse nine indicates that they were traveling

412
00:23:18,980 --> 00:23:20,540
 at a dangerous time.

413
00:23:20,540 --> 00:23:23,800
 Things were about to get worse.

414
00:23:23,800 --> 00:23:27,860
 Now some background here in ancient times.

415
00:23:27,860 --> 00:23:31,300
 Sailing the seas after September the 15th

416
00:23:31,300 --> 00:23:32,820
 was not advisable.

417
00:23:32,820 --> 00:23:35,140
 I guess a little bit like our mid-autumn festival

418
00:23:35,140 --> 00:23:36,540
 here in Hong Kong, right?

419
00:23:36,540 --> 00:23:38,620
 Cloudy weather would sit in

420
00:23:38,620 --> 00:23:41,620
 and it would make the navigation difficult

421
00:23:41,620 --> 00:23:44,980
 since sailors were able to navigate their position

422
00:23:44,980 --> 00:23:47,380
 using the position of the stars.

423
00:23:47,380 --> 00:23:51,500
 In fact, from November the 11th to March the 10th,

424
00:23:51,500 --> 00:23:56,140
 all seafaring ships stayed in port.

425
00:23:56,140 --> 00:24:00,780
 Now based on this information, Paul addresses the crew,

426
00:24:00,780 --> 00:24:03,040
 stating it seems clear

427
00:24:03,040 --> 00:24:05,960
 that the voyage is headed for disaster.

428
00:24:07,080 --> 00:24:12,080
 However, it seems that the captain believed,

429
00:24:12,080 --> 00:24:15,860
 ah, he could get them to Italy without harm.

430
00:24:15,860 --> 00:24:20,460
 Therefore the centurion listened to the advice of the captain

431
00:24:20,460 --> 00:24:22,820
 rather than the words of Paul.

432
00:24:22,820 --> 00:24:28,440
 We read this, since they should not stay at Fairhavens,

433
00:24:28,440 --> 00:24:33,440
 they set sail for Phoenix on Crete to winter there.

434
00:24:34,980 --> 00:24:39,040
 And in verse 13, we're told a favorable wind helped them

435
00:24:39,040 --> 00:24:42,160
 on their way towards Phoenix.

436
00:24:42,160 --> 00:24:46,160
 However, the weather quickly changed

437
00:24:46,160 --> 00:24:49,960
 as a violent Northeast wind rushed in upon them.

438
00:24:49,960 --> 00:24:54,360
 In fact, commentators agree that this storm is a typhoon,

439
00:24:54,360 --> 00:24:56,680
 which we in Hong Kong know very well.

440
00:24:56,680 --> 00:24:59,100
 We had a T8 last week.

441
00:24:59,100 --> 00:25:02,140
 And Luke literally writes that the ship was unable

442
00:25:02,140 --> 00:25:04,380
 to face the eye of the wind.

443
00:25:04,520 --> 00:25:09,520
 The ship became unmanageable and they had to ride it out

444
00:25:09,520 --> 00:25:14,980
 as the wind took the bloat wherever it pleased it.

445
00:25:14,980 --> 00:25:20,760
 As the wind drove the ship out to sea,

446
00:25:20,760 --> 00:25:23,020
 they were able to get some shelter,

447
00:25:23,020 --> 00:25:25,600
 providing the crew enough time

448
00:25:25,600 --> 00:25:27,900
 to bring the lifeboat onto the ship.

449
00:25:30,060 --> 00:25:35,060
 Next, the crew tied ropes to the ship

450
00:25:35,060 --> 00:25:39,040
 to keep it from breaking apart in the violent storm.

451
00:25:39,040 --> 00:25:44,080
 The crew then let's down the anchor to keep the ship

452
00:25:44,080 --> 00:25:46,140
 from drifting too far out to sea.

453
00:25:46,140 --> 00:25:53,040
 The storm is so bad that the crew must jettison

454
00:25:53,040 --> 00:25:57,360
 any extra cargo from the ship.

455
00:25:57,360 --> 00:25:59,400
 In fact, things were so bad

456
00:25:59,400 --> 00:26:02,660
 that the crew must throw overboard the ship's gear,

457
00:26:02,660 --> 00:26:05,460
 which would have included the main mask and its rigging.

458
00:26:05,460 --> 00:26:12,080
 By verse 20, we see that hope becomes lost upon the crew.

459
00:26:12,080 --> 00:26:16,680
 They do not believe they are gonna make it

460
00:26:16,680 --> 00:26:17,720
 through the storm.

461
00:26:17,720 --> 00:26:21,360
 And Paul writes in verse 20,

462
00:26:21,360 --> 00:26:26,360
 we finally gave up all hope of being saved.

463
00:26:27,360 --> 00:26:29,400
 It was in the midst of this despair

464
00:26:29,400 --> 00:26:32,720
 that Paul reminds the crew,

465
00:26:32,720 --> 00:26:34,560
 they should have listened to his words.

466
00:26:34,560 --> 00:26:36,080
 I told you so, right?

467
00:26:36,080 --> 00:26:42,440
 However, Paul is able to offer encouragement

468
00:26:42,440 --> 00:26:44,680
 because we read in verse 23,

469
00:26:44,680 --> 00:26:48,120
 the previous night, an angel of God told Paul

470
00:26:48,120 --> 00:26:52,160
 he would stand trial before Caesar in Rome

471
00:26:52,160 --> 00:26:55,160
 and all the people on the ship would not be saved.

472
00:26:55,160 --> 00:26:57,720
 The people on the ship would not lose their lives,

473
00:26:57,720 --> 00:27:03,640
 but they are not immediately to get to the destination.

474
00:27:03,640 --> 00:27:06,640
 They will run aground on some island.

475
00:27:06,640 --> 00:27:11,920
 Now fearing they would run aground on some rocky place,

476
00:27:11,920 --> 00:27:15,600
 some of the sailors tried to escape the ship

477
00:27:15,600 --> 00:27:17,560
 by getting on the lifeboat.

478
00:27:17,560 --> 00:27:20,520
 But Paul warns the centurion

479
00:27:20,520 --> 00:27:23,240
 that unless these men stay on the ship,

480
00:27:23,240 --> 00:27:26,140
 he would not have his life spared.

481
00:27:26,140 --> 00:27:31,480
 The centurion wisely listens to Paul this time

482
00:27:31,480 --> 00:27:34,280
 and cuts the rope holding the lifeboat

483
00:27:34,280 --> 00:27:36,820
 to prevent anyone from escaping.

484
00:27:36,820 --> 00:27:41,160
 At this time, we learn from the book of Acts,

485
00:27:41,160 --> 00:27:46,160
 there are 276 people on this ship.

486
00:27:46,160 --> 00:27:53,200
 Knowing that the shipwreck is imminent,

487
00:27:53,200 --> 00:27:57,800
 the crew throws grain overboard to lighten the ship,

488
00:27:57,800 --> 00:28:04,200
 which leads us to scene two, which is the shipwreck.

489
00:28:04,200 --> 00:28:09,440
 Not knowing where they are,

490
00:28:09,440 --> 00:28:12,520
 the crew sees a bay with a beach

491
00:28:12,520 --> 00:28:15,620
 and attempts to run the boat ashore.

492
00:28:15,620 --> 00:28:18,640
 Running into a reef, the ship becomes jammed

493
00:28:18,640 --> 00:28:21,800
 and the waves begin to break up the stern.

494
00:28:22,800 --> 00:28:26,160
 The soldiers plan to kill all the prisoners

495
00:28:26,160 --> 00:28:27,680
 so that no one would escape.

496
00:28:27,680 --> 00:28:31,640
 However, the centurion wants to save Paul

497
00:28:31,640 --> 00:28:35,240
 and he keeps the soldiers from carrying out their plan.

498
00:28:35,240 --> 00:28:38,520
 Those who could swim were ordered to swim to shore

499
00:28:38,520 --> 00:28:41,480
 while the rest would float on planks and debris

500
00:28:41,480 --> 00:28:43,180
 on the shipwreck to shore.

501
00:28:43,180 --> 00:28:47,920
 Once ashore, the crew find out

502
00:28:47,920 --> 00:28:51,280
 they're on the island of Malta.

503
00:28:51,280 --> 00:28:52,120
 We've got there.

504
00:28:52,120 --> 00:28:56,280
 I've been there a couple of times, it's very nice.

505
00:28:56,280 --> 00:29:01,000
 We read the local people show kindness

506
00:29:01,000 --> 00:29:02,840
 to the shipwreck crew.

507
00:29:02,840 --> 00:29:06,920
 They provide them with fire and hospitality,

508
00:29:06,920 --> 00:29:12,120
 but, and it's a big but,

509
00:29:12,120 --> 00:29:18,440
 while Paul was gathering wood, a viper,

510
00:29:19,420 --> 00:29:22,540
 one of the world's deadliest snakes,

511
00:29:22,540 --> 00:29:27,540
 came out and fastened itself onto his hand and gulp.

512
00:29:27,540 --> 00:29:32,700
 The immediate reaction of the local people

513
00:29:32,700 --> 00:29:36,280
 was that Paul was a murderer and justice was coming to him.

514
00:29:36,280 --> 00:29:40,560
 However, Paul shook off the viper.

515
00:29:40,560 --> 00:29:43,980
 He shook it off into the fire and suffered no harm.

516
00:29:43,980 --> 00:29:46,560
 The locals were waiting.

517
00:29:46,560 --> 00:29:51,180
 They expected Paul have his hand swelled up

518
00:29:51,180 --> 00:29:53,340
 or to be killed by the snake bite.

519
00:29:53,340 --> 00:29:57,320
 Obviously showing that the viper was poisonous.

520
00:29:57,320 --> 00:30:01,180
 Seeing that nothing happened to Paul,

521
00:30:01,180 --> 00:30:04,020
 the local people changed their minds

522
00:30:04,020 --> 00:30:06,480
 and they believed he was a God.

523
00:30:06,480 --> 00:30:09,620
 It's funny, isn't it?

524
00:30:09,620 --> 00:30:10,660
 People are fickle.

525
00:30:10,660 --> 00:30:12,620
 While on the island,

526
00:30:12,620 --> 00:30:16,940
 the father of one of the leading men, Publius,

527
00:30:16,940 --> 00:30:20,320
 suffered from fever and dysentery.

528
00:30:20,320 --> 00:30:23,560
 After Paul prayed and laid hands upon him,

529
00:30:23,560 --> 00:30:24,940
 the man was healed.

530
00:30:24,940 --> 00:30:28,720
